<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-the-derivative">
	<title>The derivative: sensitivity to change</title>

	<objectives>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					Measure a function's responsiveness to small changes using differentials.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Interpret the derivative as a ratio of differentials to analyze behavior.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Use the sign of a derivative to identify increasing and decreasing intervals.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Calculus is often described as the mathematics of change. Many quantities in the world change in tandem with each other:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					The pressure of a gas depends on its temperature and volume.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The demand for a product depends on its price.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The speed of a car depends on the pressure applied to the gas pedal.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The growth of a bacterial population depends on the amount of nutrients available.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The amount of traffic congestion depends on the number of cars on the road.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The brightness of a lamp depends on the electrical power supplied to it.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The time for a computer to sort a list depends on the number of items in the list.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			To understand these relationships, we need a way to quantify how <emph>sensitive</emph> one quantity is to changes in another: if we change one variable by a small amount, how much does another variable change in response?
		</p>
	</introduction>
	
	<subsection xml:id="subsec-estimating-sensitivity">
		<title>Estimating sensitivity</title>
		<p>
			<term>Kleiber's law</term> is an empirical relationship in biology that describes how the calories an organism needs to consume per day depends on its mass. If an organism with mass <m>m</m> consumes an average of <m>C</m> calories per day, then Kleiber's law states that
			<me>
				C=km^{3/4}
			</me>,
			where <m>k</m> is a constant proportionality that depends on the units and the type of organism. For example, if we measure mass in pounds, then for mammals, <m>k</m> is approximately <m>42</m>, and we have
			<me>
				C=42m^{3/4}
			</me>.
			To make it explicit that <m>C</m> depends on <m>m</m> (that is, <m>C</m> is a <term>function</term> of <m>m</m>), we can also write
			<me>
				C(m)=42m^{3/4}
			</me>.
			For example, if a cat weighs <m>9</m> pounds, we have
			<md>
				C(9)=42\cdot 9^{3/4}\approx 218.2834
			</md>,
			so it needs to consume about <m>218</m> calories per day.
		</p>
		<p>
			Now, how <emph>sensitive</emph> is the cat's caloric intake to changes in its mass? We can answer this by looking at the effect of such a change and computing the <emph>ratio</emph> of the change in calories to the change in mass.
		</p>
		<p>
			For example, suppose our hypothetical cat gains one pound, that is, <m>\Delta m=1</m> pound. Then the change in daily caloric intake would be
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta C \amp = C(10) - C(9)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 42\cdot 10^{3/4} - 42\cdot 9^{3/4}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp \approx 17.94495\text{ calories}</mrow>
			</md>.
			Hence the sensitivity of daily caloric intake to changes in mass over this interval is
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta m} \amp = \frac{C(10) - C(9)}{10-9}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp \approx \frac{17.94495\text{ calories}}{1\text{ pound}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp \approx 17.94495\text{ calories per pound}</mrow>
			</md>.
			We can also look at the sensitivity to a smaller change in mass, such as <m>\Delta m=0.1</m> pounds:
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta m} \amp = \frac{C(9.1) - C(9)}{9.1-9}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp \approx \frac{1.81614\text{ calories}}{0.1\text{ pounds}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp \approx 18.1614\text{ calories per pound}</mrow>
			</md>.
			Notice that this number is close to the value of <m>17.94495</m> we previously got for <m>\Delta m=1</m> pound.
		</p>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Estimate the sensitivity of the cat's caloric intake using <m>\Delta m=0.01</m> pounds and <m>\Delta m=0.001</m> pounds, and compare it to the previous estimates.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Estimate the sensitivity of the cat's caloric intake using <m>\Delta m=-0.1</m> pounds and <m>\Delta m=-0.01</m> pounds, and compare it to the previous estimates.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
	</subsection>
	
	<subsection>
		<title>To be added</title>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
		Small change is called a differential
		</p>
				<p>
		Notation: 
					<m>\dd{x}</m>, 
					<m>\dd{y}</m>
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
		Ratio of differentials is the derivative
		</p>
				<p>
		Notation: 
					<m>\DS\dv{y}{x}=f'(x)</m>
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
		Separate and you get 
					<m>\dd{y}=f'(x)\dd{x}</m>; this will often be the cleanest way to derive new derivative rules
		
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
		Sign analysis
		
					<ul>
						<li>
							<p>
				If 
								<m>\DS\dv{y}{x}&gt;0</m> on an interval, then 
								<m>f</m> is increasing on that interval
			
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
				If 
								<m>\DS\dv{y}{x}\lt 0</m> on an interval, then 
								<m>f</m> is decreasing on that interval
			
							</p>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</subsection>
</section>

